<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="575" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,303,429,452]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hovore, F. T." box="[321,484,429,452]" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="3" pageNumber="575" pagination="249 - 260" part="3" refId="ref3046" refString="Hovore, F. T. (1989) Records and descriptions of Costa Rican Cerambycidae, Part I: the Turrialba Valley. Insecta Mundi, 3 (4), 249 - 260." title="Records and descriptions of Costa Rican Cerambycidae, Part I: the Turrialba Valley" type="journal article" year="1989">Hovore (1989)</bibRefCitation>
reported: “ 
<emphasis box="[615,882,428,452]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Sphallambyx chabrillaci</emphasis>
[
<emphasis box="[903,932,429,452]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">sic</emphasis>
] Thomson—a single specimen of this large, black-and-yellow species, previously known from Brasil [
<emphasis box="[775,804,464,487]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">sic</emphasis>
], was beaten from dead wood in April, 15 km N Turrialba [EFGI. (Data and determination fide E. F. Giesbert.)”
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R." box="[350,629,533,556]" journalOrPublisher="Lambillionea" pageId="3" pageNumber="575" pagination="703 - 710" part="106" refId="ref3000" refString="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R. (2007) Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae). Lambillionea, 106 (4), 703 - 710. [2006]" title="Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae)" type="journal article" year="2007">Galileo &amp; Martins (2007)</bibRefCitation>
(translated): “ 
<bibRefCitation author="Hovore, F. T." box="[785,978,533,556]" journalOrPublisher="Insecta Mundi" pageId="3" pageNumber="575" pagination="249 - 260" part="3" refId="ref3046" refString="Hovore, F. T. (1989) Records and descriptions of Costa Rican Cerambycidae, Part I: the Turrialba Valley. Insecta Mundi, 3 (4), 249 - 260." title="Records and descriptions of Costa Rican Cerambycidae, Part I: the Turrialba Valley" type="journal article" year="1989">HOVORE (1989)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned 
<emphasis box="[1109,1262,532,556]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
for Costa Rica. MARTINS &amp; MONNÉ (2005) believed that the presence of this species in this country should be confirmed since 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
is only known from the east of Brazil. It is possible that the specimen mentioned by HOVORE is, in fact, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. mexicanum</emphasis>
.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
Examination of specimens from Guatemala, Costa Rica, and Panama showed that the supposition by 
<bibRefCitation author="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R." journalOrPublisher="Lambillionea" pageId="3" pageNumber="575" pagination="703 - 710" part="106" refId="ref3000" refString="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R. (2007) Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae). Lambillionea, 106 (4), 703 - 710. [2006]" title="Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae)" type="journal article" year="2007">Galileo &amp; Martins (2007)</bibRefCitation>
was correct. Also, examination of the holotype of 
<emphasis box="[888,1040,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. mexicanum</emphasis>
confirmed that the prothorax is illformed (
<figureCitation box="[242,282,741,764]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig</figureCitation>
. 9). Furthermore, apparently, the head is also abnormal, since the distance between upper eye lobes is wider than in the other specimens examined, and the head itself is somewhat wider too. According to the original description, the holotype of 
<emphasis box="[319,467,810,833]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. mexicanum</emphasis>
, the only formally known specimen, is a female. Although the left antenna of the holotype does not have the antennomeres X–XI, and the right antenna does not have the antennomeres VIII–XI, apparently the length agree with the other female (apex of antennomere IX reaching, at most, middle of the elytra), while in the males examined the apex of antennomere IX distinctly surpass middle of the elytra. However, abdominal ventrite V is notably different from all other specimens examined (males and females), even considering the evident variation found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,1249]" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R." box="[348,624,984,1007]" journalOrPublisher="Lambillionea" pageId="3" pageNumber="575" pagination="703 - 710" part="106" refId="ref3000" refString="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Martins, U. R. (2007) Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae). Lambillionea, 106 (4), 703 - 710. [2006]" title="Novos taxons em Cerambycini, Thyrsiini e Necyladopsini (Coleoptera, Cerambycinae)" type="journal article" year="2007">Galileo &amp; Martins (2007)</bibRefCitation>
(translated): “ 
<emphasis box="[781,1049,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Sphallambyx mexicanum</emphasis>
sp. nov. is similar to 
<emphasis box="[1284,1435,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
by the elytral color pattern, but differs by the scape and glabrous pronotum.” However, the scape in 
<emphasis box="[1277,1429,1018,1041]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. mexicanum</emphasis>
, although not pubescent, has long, erect and sparse setae, and the pronotum may or may not be pubescent, but never as pubescent as in 
<emphasis box="[330,484,1087,1111]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
. As additional differences between these two species we can add the following: head nearly glabrous (
<figureCitation box="[333,398,1122,1145]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) (distinctly pubescent in 
<emphasis box="[673,825,1121,1145]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[841,919,1122,1145]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
)); dorsal surface of head with distinct and deep sulcus on each side of central area (
<figureCitation box="[526,671,1157,1180]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 1, 4, 6, 8</figureCitation>
) (absent or nearly so in 
<emphasis box="[928,1078,1156,1180]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1092,1212,1157,1180]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14.11–13" captionStartId="4.[151,258,923,945]" captionTargetBox="[167,1435,203,892]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,194,902]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–14.11–13, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, male: 11, dorsal habitus; 12, lateral habitus; 13, dorsal habitus, holotype of Criodion toledopizai Melzer, 1934. 14, Sphallambyx superbum, dorsal habitus, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285118/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 11, 13</figureCitation>
)); dark area of elytra reaching base (
<figureCitation box="[313,410,1192,1215]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 1, 6</figureCitation>
) (not reaching in 
<emphasis box="[606,758,1191,1215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[774,896,1192,1215]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14.11–13" captionStartId="4.[151,258,923,945]" captionTargetBox="[167,1435,203,892]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,194,902]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–14.11–13, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, male: 11, dorsal habitus; 12, lateral habitus; 13, dorsal habitus, holotype of Criodion toledopizai Melzer, 1934. 14, Sphallambyx superbum, dorsal habitus, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285118/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Figs 11, 13</figureCitation>
)); elytra without dark band laterally on basal half (
<figureCitation box="[159,199,1226,1249]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10.1–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[196,1400,204,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[191,1400,194,1922]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10.1–9, Sphallambyx mexicanum: 1, dorsal habitus, male; 2, ventral habitus, male; 3, lateral habitus, male; 4, head and pronotum, female; 5, head, frontal view, male; 6, dorsal habitus, female; 7, ventral habitus, female; 8, head and pronotum, holotype female; 9, ventral habitus, holotype female. 10, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, head, frontal view, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285116/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig</figureCitation>
. 3) (sometimes slightly darkened on this area) (always present, and remarkably dark in 
<emphasis box="[1131,1281,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">S. chabrillacii</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1297,1374,1226,1249]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–14.11–13" captionStartId="4.[151,258,923,945]" captionTargetBox="[167,1435,203,892]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,194,902]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–14.11–13, Sphallambyx chabrillacii, male: 11, dorsal habitus; 12, lateral habitus; 13, dorsal habitus, holotype of Criodion toledopizai Melzer, 1934. 14, Sphallambyx superbum, dorsal habitus, male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1285118/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="575">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
)).
</paragraph>
